{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WfoXBLoyubobi93Qoq2E1U","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# SuperSearch - Superconductor Composition Explorer\n     2→\n     3→**Interactive visualization tool mapping 21,000+ known superconductors to identify under-explored regions that could yield novel high-Tc materials.**\n     4→\n     5→Built for [Periodic Labs](https://periodic.com) to demonstrate understanding of their superconductor discovery mission and ability to build production-quality research tools.\n     6→\n     7→![SuperSearch Preview](docs/preview.png) _(coming soon)_\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## 🎯 The Problem\n    12→\n    13→With 21,000+ known superconductors documented in literature, researchers face a challenge:\n    14→\n    15→- **Where have experimental efforts been concentrated?**\n    16→- **Which composition spaces remain under-explored?**\n    17→- **Where are the most promising \"white spaces\" for discovery?**\n    18→\n    19→Manual analysis of this landscape is time-consuming and doesn't scale.\n    20→\n    21→## 💡 The Solution\n    22→\n    23→SuperSearch uses machine learning to:\n    24→\n    25→1. **Map the landscape** - PCA reduces 81 compositional features to 2D space (73.55% variance retained)\n    26→2. **Identify families** - DBSCAN clustering reveals 3 major composition families\n    27→3. **Find opportunities** - Grid-based density analysis highlights 34 under-explored regions\n    28→4. **Enable exploration** - Interactive D3.js visualization with hover tooltips and Tc color-coding\n    29→\n    30→## 🔬 Key Insights\n    31→\n    32→From analysis of the UCI Superconductivity Database:\n    33→\n    34→- **21,263 materials** mapped to composition space\n    35→- **3 composition families** identified via clustering\n    36→- **34 under-explored regions** found adjacent to high-Tc clusters\n    37→- **Tc range:** 0-185K in dataset (avg: 34.4K)\n    38→- **High-Tc materials:** 5,872 with Tc > 50K (28%), 1,423 with Tc > 100K (7%)\n    39→\n    40→## 🚀 Why This Matters for Periodic Labs\n    41→\n    42→Your mission is accelerating superconductor discovery through AI-driven autonomous experimentation. SuperSearch complements this by:\n    43→\n    44→### 1. Research Leverage\n    45→Visualizes the experimental landscape to show where efforts have been sparse vs. concentrated.\n    46→\n    47→### 2. Hypothesis Generation\n    48→Sparse regions adjacent to high-Tc clusters = concrete targets for your autonomous lab to screen systematically.\n    49→\n    50→### 3. Strategic Planning\n    51→Shows composition families worth exploring with your Materials Project integration and GNoME predictions.\n    52→\n    53→### 4. Progress Tracking\n    54→Could integrate with your experimental results to visualize how your lab fills in white spaces over time.\n    55→\n    56→## 🛠️ Technical Stack\n    57→\n    58→- **Data:** UCI Superconductivity Database (21K materials, 81 features)\n    59→- **Analysis:** Python (pandas, scikit-learn) - PCA, DBSCAN clustering, density analysis\n    60→- **Visualization:** Vanilla JavaScript + D3.js (no framework bloat)\n    61→- **Design:** Modern dark UI inspired by materials science research tools\n    62→\n    63→## 📂 Project Structure\n    64→\n    65→```\n    66→supersearch/\n    67→├── data/\n    68→│   ├── train.csv              # UCI dataset (21K materials)\n    69→│   ├── analysis_results.json  # Processed data for viz\n    70→│   └── ...\n    71→├── web/\n    72→│   └── index.html            # Standalone visualization\n    73→├── analyze_data.py           # PCA + clustering + density analysis\n    74→├── README.md                 # This file\n    75→└── FOR_PERIODIC_LABS.md      # Detailed pitch document\n    76→```\n    77→\n    78→## 🎮 Running Locally\n    79→\n    80→```bash\n    81→# Clone the repository\n    82→git clone https://github.com/yourusername/supersearch.git\n    83→cd supersearch\n    84→\n    85→# Serve the visualization\n    86→cd web\n    87→python3 -m http.server 8000\n    88→\n    89→# Open http://localhost:8000 in your browser\n    90→```\n    91→\n    92→## 📊 Regenerate Analysis (Optional)\n    93→\n    94→If you want to modify the analysis:\n    95→\n    96→```bash\n    97→# Install dependencies\n    98→pip install pandas scikit-learn numpy\n    99→\n   100→# Run analysis\n   101→python analyze_data.py\n   102→\n   103→# Output: data/analysis_results.json\n   104→```\n   105→\n   106→## 🎨 Visualization Features\n   107→\n   108→- **Color gradient:** Tc encoded as blue → purple → pink (0K → 185K)\n   109→- **Interactive tooltips:** Hover to see material formula, Tc, cluster assignment\n   110→- **Highlighted regions:** 34 under-explored zones shown with boundary boxes\n   111→- **Zoom & pan:** Standard D3 controls for exploration\n   112→- **Responsive design:** Works on desktop and tablet\n   113→\n   114→## 🔮 Possible Extensions\n   115→\n   116→If useful for your research, could be extended to:\n   117→\n   118→1. **Integrate Materials Project data** - Overlay your predicted/synthesized materials\n   119→2. **Real-time experiment tracking** - Show where your autonomous lab has tested\n   120→3. **Filtering & search** - By crystal structure, synthesis feasibility, elements\n   121→4. **Gradient-based prioritization** - Rank sparse regions by predicted property gradients\n   122→5. **Historical tracking** - Animate how composition space has been explored over decades\n   123→\n   124→## 📈 Build Details\n   125→\n   126→- **Time:** ~8 hours from concept to production-ready\n   127→- **Lines of code:** ~400 Python (analysis) + ~600 JavaScript (viz)\n   128→- **Deployment:** Static site (no backend needed) - ready for GitHub Pages/Vercel\n   129→\n   130→## 🤝 Why I Built This\n   131→\n   132→I'm deeply interested in Periodic Labs' mission to accelerate scientific discovery through AI + autonomous experimentation. After researching your work (the GNoME paper, autonomous robotic labs), I wanted to demonstrate:\n   133→\n   134→1. **Domain understanding** - I get what you're building and why it matters\n   135→2. **Technical execution** - I can ship production-quality research tools quickly\n   136→3. **Product sense** - Focus on what's immediately useful vs. just technically impressive\n   137→4. **Rapid iteration** - Concept to working demo in hours, not weeks\n   138→\n   139→## 📬 Contact\n   140→\n   141→Built as part of application to Periodic Labs.\n   142→\n   143→**[Your Name]**  \n   144→Email: [your email]  \n   145→GitHub: [your github]  \n   146→LinkedIn: [your linkedin]\n   147→\n   148→---\n   149→\n   150→## 📄 License\n   151→\n   152→MIT License - Free to use, modify, and distribute.\n   153→\n   154→## 🙏 Acknowledgments\n   155→\n   156→- UCI Machine Learning Repository for the Superconductivity Database\n   157→- D3.js community for excellent documentation\n   158→- Periodic Labs for inspiring this project\n   159→\n   160→---\n   161→\n   162→**Looking forward to discussing how this type of analysis could complement your internal tools and contribute to your superconductor research mission.**\n   163→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01D713vsxZXeLLXCSEiA9DRw","session_id":"ea4c7d20-555a-44c2-8feb-537f7e876054","uuid":"2dc889ef-50b3-4aa2-a6af-4b1a48918efb"}
